These installation instructions are for the /dev version and will need changing for the release version.

First, download the /dev version of AirGravQC from GitHub onto a useful location on your computer. Somewhere in your Documents folder or its equivalent is typical.

The following assumes you have a conda python installation in place. If not, get one. Although it can probably be done with pip.

Install GMT:
	???

Install Jupyter Lab:
	I use the app JupyterLab Desktop (https://github.com/jupyterlab/jupyterlab-desktop?tab=readme-ov-file), but the web-based Jupyterlab Notebooks also work fine (https://jupyter.org/install).

If you don't already have an environment in which you want to do your QC work, set one up. I use conda to do this but there are other ways. Here is an example that creates a working environment called 'whizz' and installs the latest versions of python and pip into that environment. You don’t have to call it whizz.
	conda create --name whizz python pip

Make the environment the current one by activating it (again, I use conda):
	conda activate whizz

Then, since the environment is new, we need to install the following packages via conda (pip also works for many, perhaps all of these):
	conda install numpy matplotlib pathlib colorcet xarray netCDF4 rioxarray h5py pygmt scipy pooch verde jupyterlab ipympl

There are some that didn't install for me under conda, so I install them with pip (I did this one by one but maybe it can be done on one line):
	pip install filebrowser
	pip install gspy
	# skimage
	pip install scikit-image

Then install AirGravQC. The example has the path to AirGravQC on my computer. Replace this with the equivalent path on your computer.
	python3 -m pip install -e /Users/markdransfield/Documents/GitHub/AirGravQC

Now we can run python:
	python3

... and import AirGravQC. If it imports successfully, we are done and can now go to the JupyterLab workbook.
	>>> import AirGravQC as qc
